Yes—best method is a hybrid: finish members/auth first, then build by dependency slices (not random module-by-module).
That gives you working milestones and lets me connect frontend immediately after each slice.

Recommended Build Order

Phase 1: Members/Auth (finish fully)
signUp, logIn, me, getMemberProfile
updateMemberProfile, changePassword, logout (if needed)
optional: applyVendor, getMyVendorApplication
Phase 2: Catalog Read (customer browsing)
getProducts, getProduct, searchProducts, getCategories
Phase 3: Engagement
likeProduct/unlikeProduct, getLikedProducts
viewProduct (increment view count), optional recent views
Phase 4: Cart + Checkout
getCart, addToCart, updateCartItem, removeCartItem, clearCart
createOrder, getMyOrders, getOrder
Phase 5: Vendor Product Management
createProduct, updateProduct, deleteProduct, getMyProducts
Phase 6: Admin Controls
member moderation + vendor approval + product moderation
Why this is better

Keeps auth/guards stable first.
Delivers usable frontend early (browse -> like/view -> buy).
Avoids blocked work (e.g., product mutations before vendor/admin flow exists).
How we execute together

You implement one phase backend APIs.
I immediately wire frontend for that phase (queries/mutations, pages, guards, UX states).
Then we move to next phase.
If you agree, we start now with Phase 1 remaining APIs (updateMemberProfile, changePassword) before touching products.